      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/sqa-gradation2-documented-procedures",
      "rationale": "All three FEA platforms (FDA in-house code, Ansys 2021 R2, DePuy Synthes proprietary solver) operate under documented software quality assurance plans. Version control, change management, and test case regression suites are maintained per ISO 9001:2015 and FDA 21 CFR Part 820 requirements. SQA documentation reviewed and confirmed at Gradation 2 for this COU."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/ncv-gradation2-benchmark-suite",
      "rationale": "Each solver was subjected to a suite of benchmark problems drawn from ASME V&V 10 and internal FDA benchmark library, covering linear elastic beam bending and contact mechanics. Patch tests and manufactured solution checks confirm correct implementation. All three codes pass at Gradation 2 for the element types and contact algorithms used in this model."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/disc-error-gradation2-mesh-convergence",
      "rationale": "Systematic mesh refinement study performed across three mesh densities (coarse, medium, fine) for all three FEA platforms. Richardson extrapolation applied to stiffness and yield force QoIs. Grid convergence index (GCI) < 2% for all QoIs at the production mesh density. Achieved Gradation 3 exceeds the required Gradation 2 for this medium-risk COU."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nse-scoped-out-justification",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error is formally scoped out of this credibility assessment because the three independent FEA platforms employ fundamentally different solver architectures (direct sparse factorization in the FDA code, iterative PCG in Ansys, and a direct multifrontal solver in the DePuy Synthes code). The cross-platform agreement observed in the validation results — all three solvers producing QoI predictions within 5% of each other and within the 10% acceptance bound relative to experiment — provides strong indirect evidence that solver-specific numerical errors are negligible relative to other uncertainty sources. Furthermore, each solver's iterative convergence tolerance was set to 1×10⁻⁸ on the normalized residual, and residual histories were inspected to confirm monotonic convergence without stagnation. Given that solver error is dominated by the already-quantified discretization error at this mesh density, and that the multi-platform redundancy effectively bounds any platform-specific solver artifact, this factor does not contribute meaningfully to the overall credibility gap. Scoping out this factor is consistent with ASME V&V 40-2018 Section 5.3.2, which permits exclusion of factors whose contribution to prediction uncertainty is demonstrably negligible relative to the accepted uncertainty budget."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/use-error-gradation2-peer-review",
      "rationale": "Model setup, boundary condition application, material property assignment, and post-processing scripts were independently reviewed by a second analyst at each participating organization. Discrepancies were resolved prior to result submission. Formal peer-review checklist completed and archived. Use error controlled at Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-form-gradation2-constitutive-justification",
      "rationale": "Titanium alloy (Ti-6Al-4V) screw and UHMWPE block material models employ isotropic linear elasticity below yield and bilinear kinematic hardening above yield, consistent with published material characterization data. Contact between screw and block modeled with penalty-based frictional contact (μ=0.2). Model form choices are documented and justified against available material test data and prior literature. Gradation 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-inputs-gradation2-sensitivity",
      "rationale": "Sensitivity analysis performed on key material and geometric inputs (Young's modulus ±5%, yield strength ±8%, screw outer diameter ±0.05 mm, friction coefficient ±0.05). One-at-a-time sensitivity indices computed; stiffness QoI most sensitive to modulus (±3.1% output variation). Input uncertainties bounded by material certificates and dimensional inspection reports. Gradation 2 criteria met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-samples-gradation2-lot-traceability",
      "rationale": "N=11 constructs (6 from Lab 1, 5 from Lab 2) fabricated from a single manufacturing lot of non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screws. Dimensional inspection (CMM) confirmed all screws within ±0.03 mm of nominal geometry. UHMWPE blocks sourced from a single vendor lot; density and hardness verified. Sample traceability documented at Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-conditions-gradation2-multiple-conditions",
      "rationale": "Testing performed under a single ASTM F1717 loading condition (static compression-bending at 5 mm/min crosshead speed, ambient temperature). Only one test condition was explored; variation in loading rate, temperature, or angle was not investigated. This limits the factor to Gradation 1, which falls below the required Gradation 2. This gap is acknowledged and accepted based on the specific COU scope (single-condition regulatory submission) and the conservative nature of the F1717 protocol. The shortfall is documented in the decision rationale and flagged for future work if the COU is expanded to dynamic or multi-condition scenarios."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/equiv-inputs-gradation2-parameter-mapping",
      "rationale": "Each FEA model input parameter was mapped to a directly measured experimental quantity: screw geometry from CMM data, material properties from tensile coupon tests on companion specimens, friction coefficient from tribology measurements on Ti-6Al-4V/UHMWPE pairs. No surrogate or assumed values used for primary QoI-driving parameters. Equivalency confirmed at Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/output-comparison-gradation2-euval-metric",
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison performed using the E/uval metric per ASME V&V 40-2018. For all three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm): E/uval < 1.96 and percentage difference < 10%. Stiffness: E/uval = 1.12; yield force: E/uval = 0.87; force at 40 mm: E/uval = 1.31. Statistical equivalence testing (two one-sided tests, TOST) also performed and passed. Gradation 3 achieved, exceeding the required Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/qoi-relevance-scoped-out-justification",
      "rationale": "The relevance of the quantities of interest factor is formally scoped out of this credibility assessment on the grounds that the QoIs — construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement — are mandated directly by ASTM F1717 and the FDA regulatory submission pathway for spinal implant systems. These QoIs are not selected by the modeling team but are prescribed by the applicable standard and by the predicate device regulatory history. Their relevance to the clinical COU (structural integrity of the pedicle screw construct under worst-case bending loads) has been established through decades of regulatory precedent and biomechanical literature. Conducting a formal relevance assessment would be redundant with the regulatory framework that already defines these metrics as necessary and sufficient for the submission decision. This scoping decision is consistent with ASME V&V 40-2018 Section 5.3.2, which allows factors to be scoped out when their contribution to credibility uncertainty is already resolved by an authoritative external framework. The scoping is documented here for transparency and does not reduce the overall credibility of the assessment."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/val-activity-relevance-gradation2-cou-mapping",
      "rationale": "Validation activities directly replicate the COU: same screw design, same ASTM F1717 protocol, same loading mode (compression-bending), same UHMWPE block material, and same acceptance bounds used in the submission. The validation domain fully overlaps the intended use domain. No extrapolation beyond the validated envelope is claimed. Gradation 2 achieved."
    }
